{
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Specific yield strength values for individual steels were not explicitly stated, though 0.8C and 1.2C steels were noted to have similar YS values",
    "Calculated stacking fault energy (SFE) values: 73.4 mJ/m² for 0.5C steel, 77.9 mJ/m² for 0.8C steel, and 84.5 mJ/m² for 1.2C steel",
    "Calculated densities: 6.92 g/cm³ for 0.5C steel, 6.88 g/cm³ for 0.8C steel, and 6.78 g/cm³ for 1.2C steel",
    "Specific strength of 0.8C steel was calculated as 142.3 MPa cm³/g",
    "Product of strength and elongation (UTS × TE): 37597 MPa·% for 0.8C steel and 53.2 GPa% for 1.2C steel (approximately twice that of 0.5C steel)",
    "Strain hardening behavior analyzed via Crussard-Jaoul (C-J) analysis showed two-stage behavior for 0.5C and 0.8C steels, and three-stage behavior for 1.2C steel",
    "Microstructural evolution during deformation observed via interrupted tensile tests: planar slip at low strains, Taylor lattice and microbands at intermediate strains, and microband interactions at high strains in 1.2C steel",
    "0.5C steel exhibited multi-slip in austenite at low strain while 0.8C steel showed dominant single slip due to ordered phases hindering dislocation multiplication"
  ],
